				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">A Conversation With: Kalvakuntla Taraka Rama Rao, Telangana Leader</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Sriram Karri			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-02-28T11:13:26+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">February 28, 2014 6:13 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">February 28, 2014 6:13 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//india.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/02/28/a-conversation-with-kalvakuntla-taraka-rama-rao-telangana-leader/" data-title="A Conversation With: Kalvakuntla Taraka Rama Rao, Telangana Leader" data-description="India Ink spoke with Mr. Rao about the long fight for statehood and the challenges ahead for Indiaâs 29th state. ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><br />
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/28/world/asia/28-KTR-IndiaInk/28-KTR-IndiaInk-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/28/world/asia/28-KTR-IndiaInk/28-KTR-IndiaInk-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/28/world/asia/28-KTR-IndiaInk/28-KTR-IndiaInk-articleInline.jpg" id="100000002740528" width="190" height="166" alt="Kalvakuntla Taraka Rama Rao has worked tirelessly to achieve his dream of creating a separate state for the people of Telangana."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="166"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Kalvakuntla Taraka Rama Rao has worked tirelessly to achieve his dream of creating a separate state for the people of Telangana.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Courtesy of Kalvakuntla Taraka Rama Rao</span></figcaption></figure></div></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Kalvakuntla Taraka Rama Rao, an Andhra Pradesh assembly legislator and senior leader of the Telangana Rashtra Samithi party, is the son of Kalvakuntla Chandrasekhar Rao, the partyâs president, who is also considered the architect and driving force behind the </em><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/21/world/asia/indias-upper-house-approves-creation-of-new-state.html?">successful petition</a><em> for a separate Telangana state, which will be carved out of Andhra Pradesh.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>The younger Mr. Rao is the modern face of the party and its principal spokesman, and his leadership of the youth helped keep the dream of Telangana alive for more than a decade. His party eventually aligned with the Congress Party, which leads the governing coalition in New Delhi, on the issue of statehood after the Raos promised to combine their party with the Congress.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>A month ago, the father-son duo and a posse of party leaders left for Delhi with a promise: âWe are leaving from the state of Andhra Pradesh but will return to Telangana.â On Wednesday, days after securing statehood for Telangana, they returned home to a heroâs welcome.</em><span id="more-72981"></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>India Ink spoke with the younger Mr. Rao by telephone and email about the long fight for statehood, the challenges ahead, the partyâs vision for the new state, and the fears of those from the Seemandhra coastal region, who had opposed the creation of Indiaâs 29<sup>th</sup> state. </em></p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">How does it feel to have achieved your biggest goal after leading a long struggle?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We have<b> </b>often<b> </b>been<b> </b>inspired by a popular saying, that âthe power of people is far stronger than the people in power.â The Telangana movement has not only reinforced faith in democracy but has demonstrated to everyone that a nonviolent struggle can succeed in contemporary times.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We are happy, delighted. Achieving Telangana was the most glorious moment of our lives. It is a historic occasion and heralds the start of a momentum period.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But our sight is already set on the creation of a great Telangana. We have the onerous task of rebuilding our state in the way it should have been.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What is the road map and future for Telangana in more concrete terms?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Achieving Telangana was a means, not an end. An important goal ahead is to achieve real democracy: social, economic and political democracy. We have to empower our people and accord them dignity in every aspect. The most important areas of work are decentralization of power, administrative rationalizing, irrigation and rural development, universal education, welfare, health care and progress of economy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">While the manifesto will detail every plan, we can discuss a few broad aspirations. Irrigation has been a sore point of our farmers. Harnessing the huge untapped potential of major rivers Godavari and Krishna, we will have to create 10 million acres of cultivable land. Major, minor irrigation projects and revival of minor tanks and canal system built in ancient times of the Nizams have to be all harnessed. Cultivable land will achieve a social transformation for major chunks of people, who are also often the most deprived and poor.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As promised by our leader K.C.R. [Kalvakuntla Chandrasekhar Rao], we will give completely free education to all our children from backward sections. If Hyderabad Public School can create C.E.O.s for global software majors, our other schools, both government and private, have to be upgraded to achieve same standards.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We know the fact that we live in a new-age economy. Therefore, harnessing the potential of Hyderabad and surrounding areas as a major economic engine is of paramount significance. We have to consolidate its cosmopolitan nature, ensure everyoneâs safety and win the trust of the global investor community that this is a city worthy of investing their time, resources and efforts. We clearly can create over two million direct jobs and over three million indirect jobs as per the latest I.T.I.R. [Information Technology Investment Region] policy in and around Hyderabad.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We also have to improve other verticals, including pharmaceuticals, tourism and explore newer areas. Bidding for the Olympics would be a major goal ahead.</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/28/world/asia/28-kcr-IndiaInk/28-kcr-IndiaInk-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/28/world/asia/28-kcr-IndiaInk/28-kcr-IndiaInk-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/28/world/asia/28-kcr-IndiaInk/28-kcr-IndiaInk-blog480.jpg" id="100000002740538" width="480" height="320" alt="K. Chandrasekhar Rao, foreground right, president of theÂ Telangana Rashtra Samithi party, being given a hero&#039;s welcome after his arrival in Hyderabad, Andhra Pradesh, on Feb. 26."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">K. Chandrasekhar Rao, foreground right, president of theÂ Telangana Rashtra Samithi party, being given a hero's welcome after his arrival in Hyderabad, Andhra Pradesh, on Feb. 26.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Mahesh Kumar A./Associated Press</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Will you merge your party into the Congress Party as per your promise?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Elections are around the corner. We are aware that we have to decide. We have already declared that we are not considering merging into the Congress right now, but we are not in a hurry to take a decision.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">There was <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/19/world/asia/indias-lower-house-passes-bill-to-create-29th-state.html">much criticism</a> about the manner in which the Telangana bill was passed by Parliament. What is your view on how India should decide to create new states in the future?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We donât think everyone who starts an agitation should be granted a separate state. The Indian Constitution gives you a right to demand for a new state. Parliament has the right to declare a new state. The opinion of any state legislative assembly is not legally binding on Parliament. There was nothing wrong in the process adopted in passing the Telangana bill.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Yes, we did as a nation lose an opportunity for a great debate, but how can anyone hold one when a section opposed to Telangana decides to use <a href="//india.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/02/13/andhra-pradesh-lawmakers-turn-violent-after-telangana-bill-is-introduced/">pepper spray</a> to attack fellow parliamentarians? We wonât say, having achieved our goal of a separate Telangana, that newer states should not be formed. But we have to ensure as the worldâs largest democracy, this is not ad hoc but based on scientific criteria. We have states ranging in size: from those in the northeast, which have just one parliamentary seat, to Uttar Pradesh, the worldâs sixth-largest administrative unit.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But it is more important to ask this: Why should citizens have to come to the streets and conduct prolonged agitations for justice? Why should a democracy force its people to take to streets and push its youth to kill themselves before Parliament grants justice? Our democracy should be mature enough to recognize aspirations.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">How would you address the issue raised by Seemandhra politicians about safety of life and property of people living in Telangana, Hyderabad in particular?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">There is<b> </b>a fundamental flaw in their argument. All these years, when the agitation was on and emotions were high, nothing untoward happened. Why will anybodyâs lives and property be in danger now?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Hyderabad is a metro city, like New Delhi, Chennai, Mumbai or Bengaluru. Hyderabad belongs to both states as a common capital for 10 years, yet in administrative terms it belongs to Telangana. But the larger truth is that it belongs to India and all Indians. It is only a geographic division, not a divide between people.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">(This interview was condensed and lightly edited.)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><i>Sriram Karri is a freelance journalist based in Hyderabad. Find him on Twitter </i><a href="https://www.twitter.com/oratorgreat"><i>@oratorgreat</i></a><i>.</i></p>
	</div>
